      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The KIPP Academy schools (front page, Aug. 16), which require 70 percent more class time and ''are marked by militaristic discipline and rituals,'' are improving children's standardized test scores. But what a limited definition of success!</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The KIPP Academy schools (front page, Aug. 16), which require 70 percent more class time and ''are marked by militaristic discipline and rituals,'' are improving children's standardized test scores. But what a limited definition of success!</p>
        <p>Standardized tests primarily assess students' ability to memorize facts and formulas that they half understand so they can get answers that adult authorities say are correct. Test scores say nothing about children's creativity, empathy, sensitivity to nature, love of learning or ability to think for themselves.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM CRAIN  New York, Aug. 16, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of psychology at City College, CUNY.</p>
      </block>
